      <title>Re: What is Sony doing about exploit/cheaters?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=110331#M110331</link>
      <description>&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Maddar_Xegony wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;You don't get it. There are versions of the programming and add ons &lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;EM&gt;that aren't available for downloading &lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt;over the internet. Through a rather weird series of events I've ended up being close to several plat farmers without actually playing with them, exploiting, ect. and they've all mentioned having a "guy" that programmed macros for them and customized a version of the software for their use.&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;They might not be available for public download, but the macro programs are not rocket science. Been a while since I looked at it, but as I recall the macros themselves are nothing but XML files, which is not even programming - just a text file with macro steps in it. I read the boards there from time to time to get ideas on what to look for in a cheater, and from what I see very few really understand enough about the program itself to do any real programming [just as an aside, a few&amp;nbsp;weeks ago some idiot posted there bragging about how he was auto-farming, and gave his in-game name and server].&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;What SOE needs to do to stop it is to make it so that MQ2 cannot intercept, or cannot understand or translate what is sent back and forth. The real programming is in the MQ2 program itself, not in the macros. I am not a code guru - I can barely manage "hello world" in Javascript - but from what I see is that of those using MQ2, about 3% are "hackers" and 97% are script kiddies. If you can find a way to stop the script kiddies, that is a huge chuck of cheating taken out of the equation.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
